Photo: Nigel Parry

The story of McCainâ€™s captivity in Vietnam has been told so many times it can now be rendered in shorthand: 1967, a bombing raid over Hanoi, his plane shot down, both arms and a knee broken, capture, torture, the prospect of early release refused on principle, an ordeal that lasts for more than five years, much of it spent in solitary confinement, during a war that most of the country had already given up on. Itâ€™s the story that made McCainâ€™s political career, thatâ€™s been trotted out in six Senate campaigns and two presidential bids. But it also undeniably shaped McCainâ€™s view of the world and Americaâ€™s place in it. â€œI fell in love with my country when I was a prisoner in someone elseâ€™s,â€ he said during his nomination acceptance speech at the 2008 Republican convention. â€œI loved it for its decency, for its faith in the wisdom, justice, and goodness of its people. I loved it because it was not just a place but an idea, a cause worth fighting for. I was never the same again; I wasnâ€™t my own man anymore; I was my countryâ€™s.â€

McCain believes in the idea of American exceptionalism, that the United States has a responsibility to be a force for good in the world and to confront repressive regimes. The Trump doctrine â€” to the extent that one exists â€” is quite different: American foreign policy should be dictated by nationalist self-interest at almost any cost. During the 2016 campaign, Trump advocated for reintroducing torture as a means of extracting information, killing terroristsâ€™ families, and seizing Iraqâ€™s oil. He derided international institutions such as NATO and the U.N. and cheered when Britain voted to pull out of the European Union. He praised brutal strongmen from Saddam Hussein to Vladimir Putin, whom heâ€™s called a more impressive leader than Barack Obama.

McCain has been arguing for years that Putinâ€™s Russia is a global menace that must be confronted. â€œRussiaâ€™s leaders, rich with oil wealth and corrupt with power, have rejected democratic ideals and the obligations of a responsible power,â€ McCain said during his 2008 RNC speech. â€œThey invaded a small, democratic neighbor to gain more control over the worldâ€™s oil supply, intimidate other neighbors, and further their ambitions of reassembling the Russian empire.â€ He sees Russia as a bully with designs on rolling back the spread of democracy in Eastern Europe and controlling the Middle East with Iran, fundamentally threatening Americaâ€™s place in the world. â€œPutin wonâ€™t stop until the cost of going forward is too high,â€ McCain told me.

The senator has challenged presidents of both parties when their foreign-policy directives ran counter to his own. In his first term in Congress, he criticized Ronald Reaganâ€™s decision to station peacekeeping Marines in Beirut with minimal defenses, which resulted in the deaths of 241 service personnel when a suicide bomber drove straight into the barracks. His battles with George W. Bush over tax cuts, torture, and U.S. strategy in Iraq became the stuff of Washington lore. And during the Obama years, McCain was one of the presidentâ€™s fiercest foreign-policy critics, finding fault with his decision to pull troops from Iraq and his refusal to enforce his â€œred lineâ€ on Syria after Bashar al-Assad used chemical weapons against his people.

And yet it would be grossly inaccurate to characterize McCain as a man of pure principle. Heâ€™s too complicated for that. What makes him inspiring â€” and infuriating â€” to people on both sides of the aisle is that, more than most politicians, his political acts span a particularly wide distance between courage and expediency. He is capable of true heroism and conspicuous political cowardice. Over the years, heâ€™s flip-flopped on some of his signature issues, from unfunded tax cuts to immigration reform to upholding Roe v. Wade. Heâ€™s often on the phone, dialing up friends and advisers to gauge their opinions and weigh the risks and rewards of various courses of action.

I get along with the Democrats, but please, Iâ€™m not their hero. Theyâ€™re trying to use us. We will work with them, but have no doubt, their agenda is not our agenda.

This is how it came to be that the same McCain who cares so deeply about Americaâ€™s standing in the world also cynically named as his â€™08 running mate Sarah Palin, thus arguably ushering in the era of Trumpism that he now finds so troubling. He still defends the choice. â€œThe media went after her like Iâ€™ve never seen,â€ he told me. â€œThey said she said, â€˜Oh, I can see Russia from here.â€™ Well, Russia is not that far from Alaska! They destroyed her in a way I will never forgive them.â€ In private, he has been more candid. â€œI regret running a small campaign,â€ he told a friend.

Still, according to his advisers, McCainâ€™s reaction to Trump is mostly from the point of view of his better angels. To an extent far greater than McCain himself will say, they describe McCain as finding Trump to be a true threat to the republic. McCain speechwriter Mark Salter said the Trump administration presents a challenge to the senatorâ€™s core values. â€œMcCain has always had empathy and compassion for oppressed people. It affects his views on torture and the way we should conduct ourselves in the world. Itâ€™s anathema to the Trump-Bannon-Sessions worldview. Thatâ€™s not really Realpolitik â€” itâ€™s fanatical. Itâ€™s bleak. Take their oil? Kill their families? Itâ€™s like a cartoon villain and is against everything John McCain stands for.â€

The antipathy between the two started during the campaign when McCain criticized Trump for calling Mexicans â€œrapists,â€ attacking an Indiana-born judge of Mexican descent, and denigrating the Muslim parents of a slain Iraq War soldier. Trump said McCain wasnâ€™t a â€œwar heroâ€ because heâ€™d been captured by the North Vietnamese and so couldnâ€™t fight (â€œI like people that werenâ€™t captured,â€ said Trump). Trump adviser Steve Bannonâ€™s media arm, Breitbart, has gone after McCain repeatedly, even claiming he created isis. â€œBannon, who I donâ€™t know, was clearly doing the stories,â€ McCain told me. On top of that, Trumpâ€™s financial backers, Robert and Rebekah Mercer, donated heavily to a PAC backing McCainâ€™s pro-Trump primary challenger.

