â€œMcCain is a savvy political operator,â€ a former adviser said. â€œHe sees a critical mass building demanding investigations. He weighs in at the decisive moment to turn it to calls for a select committee, and ultimately heâ€™ll be the person that tips it to calls for an independent-counsel investigation.â€ If that happens, who knows what will be found? Suspicions are both dire and plausible. It was, after all, an independent counsel looking into Whitewater that led to the Monica Lewinsky scandal. â€œIf itâ€™s found that there was collusion between senior officials in the Trump campaign and the Russian Federation, is that a criminal act? It puts us in uncharted waters,â€ said the adviser.

McCain has been tracking the Russia issue since shortly before Thanksgiving, when he ran into Sir Andrew Wood, a former British ambassador to Moscow, at the Halifax Security Forum, a foreign-policy conference. Wood tipped McCain off about the now-infamous dossier that claimed Putin had compiled embarrassing information on Trump that could be used for blackmail, as well as allegations that the Trump campaign coordinated with Kremlin officials. â€œI didnâ€™t know what to make of it,â€ said McCain, â€œbut everyone knows the Russians do use women and sex when people go to Russia. Itâ€™s an old KGB honeypot.â€

